                                                   Bond and Tuffey named in probables
                      
	 Christchurch: New Zealand Cricket (NZC) Thursday named former Indian Cricket League (ICL) players Shane Bond and Daryl Tuffey in the 30 probables for the forthcoming Champions Trophy in South Africa.         
	Incidentally, Bond and Tuffey were recalled in the New Zealand ODI squad and Twenty20 team for next months tour of Sri Lanka.         
	THE probables         
	Daniel Vettori, Brent Arnel, Shane Bond, Neil Broom, Ian Butler, Craig Cumming, Brendon Diamanti, Grant Elliott, James Franklin, Peter Fulton, Martin Guptill, Gareth Hopkins, Jamie How, Peter Ingram, Brendon McCullum, Nathan McCullum, Peter McGlashan, James Marshall, Chris Martin, Kyle Mills, Iain Brien, Jacob Oram, Jeetan Patel, Aaron Redmond, Jesse Ryder, Shanan Stewart, Tim Southee, Scott Styris, Ross Taylor and Daryl Tuffey.               
	 Jalandhar: As the clamour against the doosra gained momentum in Australia, star Indian off-spinner Harbhajan Singh on Thursday sprang in defence of the delivery that has earned him many wickets.         
	May be that is the view in Australia and I have nothing to do with it. In rest of the cricket-playing countries, including India, every player wants to add variations to his bowling and I think all the youngsters should learn it, Harbhajan said.               
	 London: Next seasons English county cricket programme will feature just one Twenty20 competition after ECB officials confirmed Thursday that plans for a second Twenty20 event had been scrapped.               
	 London: Durhams Riverside ground will host the first Ashes Test of the 2013 series, the England and Wales Cricket Board (ECB) said on Thursday. The ECB said it had accepted the recommendations of the independent Major Match Group (MMG) and also confirmed one of the five-match series would take place at the Oval in London. The three other Tests are still to be allocated and the ECB said bids will be invited.               
	 Islamabad: Pakistan has ruled out holding its share of 2011 World Cup matches at a neutral venue. Theres no such clause in the agreement among the four co-hosts, so its not possible, Pakistan Cricket Board chairman Ejaz Butt told reporters.           AGENCIES                                                                                                                   
